1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,960

2
00:00:05,960 --> 00:00:08,970
Welcome to the 2025
Gardener Lecture.

3
00:00:08,970 --> 00:00:09,770
I'm Julie Shah.

4
00:00:09,770 --> 00:00:12,090
I'm the department
head here at AeroAstro.

5
00:00:12,090 --> 00:00:15,660
And this is a very exciting
event that we hold each year.

6
00:00:15,660 --> 00:00:19,490
And so thank you so much for all
coming out to be a part of it.

7
00:00:19,490 --> 00:00:22,820
The Gardner Lecture is
made possible by a bequest

8
00:00:22,820 --> 00:00:26,300
of the late Major Lester D.
Gardner, a member of the MIT

9
00:00:26,300 --> 00:00:30,440
class of 1898, to sponsor
annual presentations

10
00:00:30,440 --> 00:00:32,450
on aeronautical history.

11
00:00:32,450 --> 00:00:34,890
He was an air officer
in World War One.

12
00:00:34,890 --> 00:00:37,860
And he was the recipient of
numerous aeronautical awards,

13
00:00:37,860 --> 00:00:41,310
including the Daniel
Guggenheim Medal in 1947,

14
00:00:41,310 --> 00:00:44,360
given for the citation for
Outstanding Achievement

15
00:00:44,360 --> 00:00:45,930
in Advancing Aeronautics.

16
00:00:45,930 --> 00:00:47,905
He had a long and
storied career.

17
00:00:47,905 --> 00:00:49,280
He established a
publishing group

18
00:00:49,280 --> 00:00:52,370
that's responsible for a number
of major aeronautical trade

19
00:00:52,370 --> 00:00:56,060
publications, including the
predecessor to Aviation Week.

20
00:00:56,060 --> 00:00:58,250
And he was also the
founder of the Institute

21
00:00:58,250 --> 00:01:00,640
for Aeronautical
Sciences, which eventually

22
00:01:00,640 --> 00:01:03,040
evolved to become our AIAA.

23
00:01:03,040 --> 00:01:05,890
Major Gardner's interest
in MIT and our department

24
00:01:05,890 --> 00:01:07,870
continued throughout his life.

25
00:01:07,870 --> 00:01:11,200
And it lives on not only in
this Gardner Lecture, which

26
00:01:11,200 --> 00:01:13,580
is a big, important event
for us in the department,

27
00:01:13,580 --> 00:01:15,620
but also in the
Hunsaker professorship,

28
00:01:15,620 --> 00:01:17,240
which he helped to establish.

29
00:01:17,240 --> 00:01:19,120
And in his honor, we
continue the tradition

30
00:01:19,120 --> 00:01:21,100
of hosting the Gardner
Lecture to celebrate

31
00:01:21,100 --> 00:01:24,040
our history and our field,
and to keep looking ahead

32
00:01:24,040 --> 00:01:25,370
by looking up.

33
00:01:25,370 --> 00:01:28,000
And so over the years,
our Gardner Lectures

34
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:32,600
have included Grover Loening;
Igor Sikorsky; Yvonne Brill;

35
00:01:32,600 --> 00:01:36,260
Neil Armstrong; Robert
Seamans, Jr.; John Langford;

36
00:01:36,260 --> 00:01:38,920
Pam Melroy, just to name a few.

37
00:01:38,920 --> 00:01:41,930
And so with that incredible
history under our belts,

38
00:01:41,930 --> 00:01:44,710
it's my great pleasure
to welcome and introduce

39
00:01:44,710 --> 00:01:47,510
this year's Gardner
speaker, Dave Limp.

40
00:01:47,510 --> 00:01:50,860
Dave is CEO of Blue Origin,
a private space company

41
00:01:50,860 --> 00:01:53,620
founded by Jeff Bezos, with a
vision of millions of people

42
00:01:53,620 --> 00:01:56,480
living and working in space
for the benefit of Earth.

43
00:01:56,480 --> 00:02:00,320
And as you all know, the company
builds reusable rocket engines,

44
00:02:00,320 --> 00:02:04,070
launch vehicles and space
systems and lunar landers.

45
00:02:04,070 --> 00:02:07,460
So Dave joined Blue
Origin as CEO in 2023.

46
00:02:07,460 --> 00:02:10,240
And he also serves as the board
chair for Blue Origin's Club

47
00:02:10,240 --> 00:02:13,030
for the Future, which is a
nonprofit organization dedicated

48
00:02:13,030 --> 00:02:15,280
to inspiring and mobilizing
future generations

49
00:02:15,280 --> 00:02:17,440
to pursue careers in STEM.

50
00:02:17,440 --> 00:02:21,260
Dave has previously been
at Amazon, since 2010,

51
00:02:21,260 --> 00:02:23,740
where he oversaw the
development, retail sales,

52
00:02:23,740 --> 00:02:26,740
and operational aspects of
Amazon's consumer electronics

53
00:02:26,740 --> 00:02:29,390
devices and the
services behind them.

54
00:02:29,390 --> 00:02:33,400
So, including Alexa,
Echo, Kindle, Fire TV,

55
00:02:33,400 --> 00:02:37,660
Ring, just to name a few, as
well as other initiatives,

56
00:02:37,660 --> 00:02:39,730
such as Project Kuiper.

57
00:02:39,730 --> 00:02:45,100
And many MIT alumni have gone
on to work at Blue Origin.

58
00:02:45,100 --> 00:02:47,680
And we've also had quite
a few research payloads

59
00:02:47,680 --> 00:02:50,570
launch on Blue Origin's
New Shepard rockets.

60
00:02:50,570 --> 00:02:54,280
So now, with Dave at
the helm, Blue Origin

61
00:02:54,280 --> 00:02:57,540
is exploring increasingly
ever more exciting

62
00:02:57,540 --> 00:03:00,300
missions and aerospace
engineering challenges

63
00:03:00,300 --> 00:03:02,980
that are truly at the
cutting edge of spaceflight.

64
00:03:02,980 --> 00:03:05,350
And he's here today to
tell us all about it.

65
00:03:05,350 --> 00:03:07,750
So please join me
in welcoming Dave.

66
00:03:07,750 --> 00:03:10,914
[APPLAUSE]

67
00:03:10,914 --> 00:03:11,820

68
00:03:11,820 --> 00:03:14,790
Thank you.

69
00:03:14,790 --> 00:03:16,635
Thank you, Professor Shah.

70
00:03:16,635 --> 00:03:18,930
I hear the previous
speakers on this

71
00:03:18,930 --> 00:03:22,110
and the quote from Wayne's
World pops up in my head,

72
00:03:22,110 --> 00:03:23,080
that I'm not worthy.

73
00:03:23,080 --> 00:03:28,900
So I'm going to do my best
to give you little words.

74
00:03:28,900 --> 00:03:32,400
Hopefully, they inspire
you in some ways.

75
00:03:32,400 --> 00:03:34,900
This lecture series
goes back to 1959.

76
00:03:34,900 --> 00:03:38,340
And it's just an amazing
honor to be here.

77
00:03:38,340 --> 00:03:41,640
I want to talk
today about how we

78
00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:47,070
as a collective species,
and specifically this class

79
00:03:47,070 --> 00:03:50,730
and you all, given your
focus on aerospace,

80
00:03:50,730 --> 00:03:52,930
can help build a road to space.

81
00:03:52,930 --> 00:03:56,270
This is a big, really
important mission in our mind

82
00:03:56,270 --> 00:03:59,930
and one that's going to
take multigenerations to do.

83
00:03:59,930 --> 00:04:02,000
But it is critically important.

84
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:03,500
And so to plant
that seed, I'm going

85
00:04:03,500 --> 00:04:04,890
to start with a quick video.

86
00:04:04,890 --> 00:04:06,740
And then we can
talk about something

87
00:04:06,740 --> 00:04:09,330
that is seemingly small.

88
00:04:09,330 --> 00:04:13,230
But is the seed that plants
this very, very large vision.

89
00:04:13,230 --> 00:04:14,600
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

90
00:04:14,600 --> 00:04:19,880
- Holy cats, weightlessness.

91
00:04:19,880 --> 00:04:21,540
Oh, Jesus.

92
00:04:21,540 --> 00:04:23,840
[LAUGHTER]

93
00:04:23,840 --> 00:04:26,570
Oh, my God.

94
00:04:26,570 --> 00:04:29,210
Oh, wow.

95
00:04:29,210 --> 00:04:33,440
I can't believe this.

96
00:04:33,440 --> 00:04:36,690
Everybody in the world
needs to see this.

97
00:04:36,690 --> 00:04:38,165
- Stand by, touchdown.

98
00:04:38,165 --> 00:04:40,910
Stand by, touchdown.

99
00:04:40,910 --> 00:04:45,320
- There is Mother
Earth and comfort.

100
00:04:45,320 --> 00:04:49,250
But what you see is black.

101
00:04:49,250 --> 00:04:53,030
Oh, my God.

102
00:04:53,030 --> 00:04:55,070
I hope I never
recover from this.

103
00:04:55,070 --> 00:04:59,240
I hope that I can
maintain what I feel now.

104
00:04:59,240 --> 00:05:02,216
I don't want to lose it.

105
00:05:02,216 --> 00:05:04,630
[LAUGHTER]

106
00:05:04,630 --> 00:05:09,340
What you have given me is
the most profound experience

107
00:05:09,340 --> 00:05:11,800
I can imagine.

108
00:05:11,800 --> 00:05:16,460
I'm so filled with emotion
about what just happened.

109
00:05:16,460 --> 00:05:18,550
Jesus.

110
00:05:18,550 --> 00:05:20,500
Oh, my God.

111
00:05:20,500 --> 00:05:21,936
It was unbelievable.

112
00:05:21,936 --> 00:05:25,360

113
00:05:25,360 --> 00:05:26,820
Oh, I'm telling you--

114
00:05:26,820 --> 00:05:29,460

115
00:05:29,460 --> 00:05:31,300
[END PLAYBACK]

116
00:05:31,300 --> 00:05:33,710
You saw Bill there.

117
00:05:33,710 --> 00:05:35,710
And there's been
over 700 people that

118
00:05:35,710 --> 00:05:39,680
have gone above the Karman line
and had their version of this.

119
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:43,790
I've been super lucky to
meet a number of astronauts,

120
00:05:43,790 --> 00:05:45,080
a pretty significant number.

121
00:05:45,080 --> 00:05:47,710
And Julie and I have
seen a few of them

122
00:05:47,710 --> 00:05:50,150
in some of the same conferences.

123
00:05:50,150 --> 00:05:51,340
And to a T--

124
00:05:51,340 --> 00:05:53,290
I haven't met them
all-- but to a T,

125
00:05:53,290 --> 00:05:57,978
they all have a similar story
to what you just saw Bill have.

126
00:05:57,978 --> 00:05:59,270
There's actually a name for it.

127
00:05:59,270 --> 00:06:00,710
It's the overview effect.

128
00:06:00,710 --> 00:06:04,330
And everybody comes
back from space

129
00:06:04,330 --> 00:06:06,470
changed in many different ways.

130
00:06:06,470 --> 00:06:09,350
But one common thread
is this overview effect.

131
00:06:09,350 --> 00:06:12,970
And it's the sense that as soon
as you leave the atmosphere,

132
00:06:12,970 --> 00:06:17,440
you see how thin of a
line there is protecting

133
00:06:17,440 --> 00:06:19,010
this great planet, Earth.

134
00:06:19,010 --> 00:06:23,410
And then you look up and you
see the deep darkness of space

135
00:06:23,410 --> 00:06:25,400
and see how vast it is.

136
00:06:25,400 --> 00:06:29,660
And you come back with a
feeling that Earth is small,

137
00:06:29,660 --> 00:06:34,180
Earth is fragile, and
Earth should be protected.

138
00:06:34,180 --> 00:06:37,790
And we've sent-- with lots of
people in this room's help--

139
00:06:37,790 --> 00:06:40,670
probes to all the moons--

140
00:06:40,670 --> 00:06:43,850
most of the moons-- all the
planetary bodies we've crossed.

141
00:06:43,850 --> 00:06:47,530
And rest assured, the
Earth is the good planet

142
00:06:47,530 --> 00:06:49,630
if you want to live.

143
00:06:49,630 --> 00:06:51,740
And we know that now.

144
00:06:51,740 --> 00:06:55,440
And so our purpose
is to figure out

145
00:06:55,440 --> 00:06:59,550
how to think about
that in that context

146
00:06:59,550 --> 00:07:03,190
and preserve that
which is the Earth.

147
00:07:03,190 --> 00:07:07,470
And to do that, we have
to think about what

148
00:07:07,470 --> 00:07:10,270
has happened over the
past couple hundred years.

149
00:07:10,270 --> 00:07:12,420
If you go back a
couple hundred years,

150
00:07:12,420 --> 00:07:16,320
and you think about almost every
metric that we would measure

151
00:07:16,320 --> 00:07:22,060
prosperity by, life expectancy
is up from 40 to 75 years,

152
00:07:22,060 --> 00:07:26,670
infant mortality is decreased
from 175 deaths per 1,000

153
00:07:26,670 --> 00:07:28,830
to less than 28.

154
00:07:28,830 --> 00:07:31,245
Global literacy is
at an all time high,

155
00:07:31,245 --> 00:07:33,490
highly correlated to prosperity.

156
00:07:33,490 --> 00:07:35,550
Poverty rates are below 10%.

157
00:07:35,550 --> 00:07:37,210
Hunger is at an all-time low.

158
00:07:37,210 --> 00:07:39,460
I could go on and
on and on again.

159
00:07:39,460 --> 00:07:43,710
And you would find reasons why
our lives are incredibly better

160
00:07:43,710 --> 00:07:45,030
than they were.

161
00:07:45,030 --> 00:07:47,740
There's one notable
difference, though.

162
00:07:47,740 --> 00:07:49,860
That notable
difference is, I can't

163
00:07:49,860 --> 00:07:52,370
go down to the Charles
River, ladle up

164
00:07:52,370 --> 00:07:56,490
a good scoop of that
water and drink it.

165
00:07:56,490 --> 00:07:59,030
We've paid the price
of all this prosperity

166
00:07:59,030 --> 00:08:01,790
by using some of the
natural resources that

167
00:08:01,790 --> 00:08:02,750
are on this Earth.

168
00:08:02,750 --> 00:08:05,630
By any dimension,
it's more polluted.

169
00:08:05,630 --> 00:08:07,620
We could argue how
much warmer it is.

170
00:08:07,620 --> 00:08:11,190
But the fact of the matter is,
it's still the great planet.

171
00:08:11,190 --> 00:08:15,680
And our job is to try to
figure out how to preserve it.

172
00:08:15,680 --> 00:08:20,210
And this is the foundation of
our mission statement, which

173
00:08:20,210 --> 00:08:25,400
is, in a simplified way, we want
to take the polluting industries

174
00:08:25,400 --> 00:08:28,110
and move them to space.

175
00:08:28,110 --> 00:08:31,770
And then we can rezone this
great planet of ours, Earth,

176
00:08:31,770 --> 00:08:36,049
to parks, recreation, maybe
a little light industry,

177
00:08:36,049 --> 00:08:37,778
roller coasters, you name it.

178
00:08:37,778 --> 00:08:39,320
But it's going to
be a place that you

179
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:40,409
can come back and visit.

180
00:08:40,409 --> 00:08:41,820
Some people still live here.

181
00:08:41,820 --> 00:08:45,080
And we'll be prosperous
in space and preserve

182
00:08:45,080 --> 00:08:47,940
that which is the thing
we love about Earth.

183
00:08:47,940 --> 00:08:50,880
So for the next 20,
25 minutes or so,

184
00:08:50,880 --> 00:08:54,510
I'm going to try to paint a
blueprint of the infrastructure,

185
00:08:54,510 --> 00:08:55,893
the key pieces.

186
00:08:55,893 --> 00:08:57,060
And they're not all of them.

187
00:08:57,060 --> 00:08:58,143
They're not all-inclusive.

188
00:08:58,143 --> 00:08:59,870
But some of the key
pieces that we think

189
00:08:59,870 --> 00:09:03,860
are critical to invent, to
make this a reality as we

190
00:09:03,860 --> 00:09:06,830
move forward.

191
00:09:06,830 --> 00:09:12,090
So the first thing I would say
is that to get this to happen,

192
00:09:12,090 --> 00:09:15,090
space needs fundamental
infrastructure.

193
00:09:15,090 --> 00:09:18,080
And if you think about the
building blocks of any step

194
00:09:18,080 --> 00:09:20,210
function change, as
you think about how

195
00:09:20,210 --> 00:09:22,740
to get to a big
vision like this,

196
00:09:22,740 --> 00:09:27,080
it is the infrastructure that
you actually think about.

197
00:09:27,080 --> 00:09:30,500
I have a front row seat to this
because I've spent a lot of time

198
00:09:30,500 --> 00:09:31,350
with Jeff.

199
00:09:31,350 --> 00:09:36,030
And Jeff tells the story of
this in the context of Amazon.

200
00:09:36,030 --> 00:09:39,110
So let me tell you that
story about Amazon.

201
00:09:39,110 --> 00:09:42,620
Jeff started Amazon in
a garage in Seattle.

202
00:09:42,620 --> 00:09:44,490
It's just him, a
couple other people.

203
00:09:44,490 --> 00:09:47,092
And yet now you look ahead
and it is your new normal.

204
00:09:47,092 --> 00:09:48,300
What would you do without it?

205
00:09:48,300 --> 00:09:49,940
How would you get
packages delivered to you?

206
00:09:49,940 --> 00:09:50,857
How would you do this?

207
00:09:50,857 --> 00:09:54,620
But how does one or two or three
people do this in a garage?

208
00:09:54,620 --> 00:09:57,640
It's because they
had infrastructure

209
00:09:57,640 --> 00:09:59,210
that they could rely on.

210
00:09:59,210 --> 00:10:01,730
They were standing on
the shoulders of giants.

211
00:10:01,730 --> 00:10:04,550
They didn't have to build an
entire transportation network.

212
00:10:04,550 --> 00:10:08,240
There was UPS, there was FedEx,
there was the postal system.

213
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:11,043
They didn't have to build
new payment systems.

214
00:10:11,043 --> 00:10:12,460
There were credit
card companies--

215
00:10:12,460 --> 00:10:14,570
Visa, Mastercard,
American Express.

216
00:10:14,570 --> 00:10:15,680
All those existed.

217
00:10:15,680 --> 00:10:17,540
So you didn't have
to go build that.

218
00:10:17,540 --> 00:10:20,540
You didn't have to build
that which was the internet.

219
00:10:20,540 --> 00:10:23,740
That was on the backs
of DARPA and Xerox PARC

220
00:10:23,740 --> 00:10:25,480
and a lot of other
research institutions

221
00:10:25,480 --> 00:10:26,980
that had built
this infrastructure

222
00:10:26,980 --> 00:10:29,150
to be able to move bits around.

223
00:10:29,150 --> 00:10:32,650
And so the young entrepreneur
that was Jeff at that time

224
00:10:32,650 --> 00:10:35,570
could focus on building
the application layer,

225
00:10:35,570 --> 00:10:40,930
knowing that all that
infrastructure existed for him.

226
00:10:40,930 --> 00:10:43,850
And we want to do the
same thing for space,

227
00:10:43,850 --> 00:10:48,640
build that infrastructure such
that when your kids' kids--

228
00:10:48,640 --> 00:10:51,760
it's likely a multi-generation
thing-- wake up and decide,

229
00:10:51,760 --> 00:10:55,980
gosh, I want to do X in space,
they can take it for granted

230
00:10:55,980 --> 00:10:58,720
that all the hard,
heavy lifting is there

231
00:10:58,720 --> 00:11:01,080
and focus on the
application layer of what

232
00:11:01,080 --> 00:11:03,660
they want to bring to market.

233
00:11:03,660 --> 00:11:06,078
So what do we want to do?

234
00:11:06,078 --> 00:11:08,370
I'm going to give you a couple
different infrastructure

235
00:11:08,370 --> 00:11:10,450
pieces, selfishly that
Blue is working on.

236
00:11:10,450 --> 00:11:12,970
But there's lots of other
people working on this as well.

237
00:11:12,970 --> 00:11:16,860
The first is we have
to dramatically reduce

238
00:11:16,860 --> 00:11:20,070
the cost of launch,
specifically, dramatically

239
00:11:20,070 --> 00:11:23,130
reduce the cost of a
kilogram of payload

240
00:11:23,130 --> 00:11:26,110
to the orbit of your choice.

241
00:11:26,110 --> 00:11:28,980
One of the hardest
things here is, in fact,

242
00:11:28,980 --> 00:11:34,150
getting payload to space
in an affordable manner.

243
00:11:34,150 --> 00:11:36,000
Now, we've done this.

244
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:39,010
You can go all the way
back to the Apollo program.

245
00:11:39,010 --> 00:11:42,780
And we got a lot of mass
all the way to the Moon.

246
00:11:42,780 --> 00:11:45,360
It came in an incredible cost.

247
00:11:45,360 --> 00:11:48,310
At the peak Apollo,
it was spending--

248
00:11:48,310 --> 00:11:52,050
there's different estimates on
this-- but spending about 2.5%

249
00:11:52,050 --> 00:11:53,680
of GDP per year.

250
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:56,020
That is an unfathomable
amount of money.

251
00:11:56,020 --> 00:12:00,612
Give me 2.5% of GDP, I will
give you fusion in 10 years.

252
00:12:00,612 --> 00:12:02,170
But it's not going to happen.

253
00:12:02,170 --> 00:12:06,540
And even at the end of
Apollo, the American people

254
00:12:06,540 --> 00:12:07,900
got fed up with it.

255
00:12:07,900 --> 00:12:09,698
It was too much of a
drag on the economy.

256
00:12:09,698 --> 00:12:11,490
And it had to be slowed
down and eventually

257
00:12:11,490 --> 00:12:15,040
shut down because it's
unsustainable at those rates.

258
00:12:15,040 --> 00:12:18,060
But you can do amazing
things in space

259
00:12:18,060 --> 00:12:19,660
if you have the
ability to do this.

260
00:12:19,660 --> 00:12:23,410
So our job as this industry,
and certainly at Blue,

261
00:12:23,410 --> 00:12:26,550
is how to take the amount
of price of that kilogram

262
00:12:26,550 --> 00:12:27,910
to orbit and bring it down?

263
00:12:27,910 --> 00:12:29,800
And you can start
seeing this on a curve.

264
00:12:29,800 --> 00:12:31,080
It's a logarithmic curve--

265
00:12:31,080 --> 00:12:33,670
dollars on one axis and
then years on the other.

266
00:12:33,670 --> 00:12:37,510
And you can start seeing where
the knee in the curve happened.

267
00:12:37,510 --> 00:12:40,800
And specifically, where
that started happening,

268
00:12:40,800 --> 00:12:42,990
is when you started to
see the introduction

269
00:12:42,990 --> 00:12:44,610
of reusable rockets.

270
00:12:44,610 --> 00:12:48,617
When you get in your car and you
drive from point A to point B,

271
00:12:48,617 --> 00:12:50,450
you don't throw away
your car into the ocean

272
00:12:50,450 --> 00:12:51,510
at the end of the trip.

273
00:12:51,510 --> 00:12:53,690
Similarly, when you get
on a Southwest Airlines

274
00:12:53,690 --> 00:12:57,590
and you fly point A to point
B, they don't scrap the plane.

275
00:12:57,590 --> 00:13:00,900
Yet, for the last 50 years,
except for the last 10,

276
00:13:00,900 --> 00:13:02,750
that is how we treated rockets.

277
00:13:02,750 --> 00:13:03,750
We just got rid of them.

278
00:13:03,750 --> 00:13:04,880
They were disposable.

279
00:13:04,880 --> 00:13:08,220
And so reusability is a key.

280
00:13:08,220 --> 00:13:11,270
And Professor Shah
mentioned that you've

281
00:13:11,270 --> 00:13:13,160
seen some of this in
some of your classwork

282
00:13:13,160 --> 00:13:16,290
because we have a
suborbital reusable vehicle.

283
00:13:16,290 --> 00:13:21,560
And it's incredibly profound
that things like this

284
00:13:21,560 --> 00:13:24,000
are our new normal.

285
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:27,050
Just 10 years ago,
this was the thing

286
00:13:27,050 --> 00:13:28,970
that science fiction
was made up of,

287
00:13:28,970 --> 00:13:31,790
that the idea that we would
be landing rockets literally

288
00:13:31,790 --> 00:13:33,740
every other day,
or every third day

289
00:13:33,740 --> 00:13:36,890
right now, orbital,
suborbital, is just

290
00:13:36,890 --> 00:13:39,600
an amazing and profound change.

291
00:13:39,600 --> 00:13:42,290
And this reuse is
completely new.

292
00:13:42,290 --> 00:13:46,090
And on the booster
side, it dramatically

293
00:13:46,090 --> 00:13:47,300
changes the formula.

294
00:13:47,300 --> 00:13:50,990
And as we start thinking
about reusing second stages,

295
00:13:50,990 --> 00:13:52,430
it furthers that formula.

296
00:13:52,430 --> 00:13:54,880
And you can see us
continuing to climb down

297
00:13:54,880 --> 00:13:57,916
