314
00:14:28,880 --> 00:14:33,400
But anyway, this is a
very famous formula that

315
00:14:33,400 --> 00:14:35,390
tells us a lot about delta-v.

316
00:14:35,390 --> 00:14:39,160
But one of the most incredible
things that it says is--

317
00:14:39,160 --> 00:14:42,050
it's a function of wet
mass over dry mass.

318
00:14:42,050 --> 00:14:45,190
And it leads you to a lot
of different conclusions.

319
00:14:45,190 --> 00:14:48,660
The one I'll focus on here
today is that it leads you--

320
00:14:48,660 --> 00:14:50,880
that rockets want to be bigger.

321
00:14:50,880 --> 00:14:53,940
As rockets get bigger,
that mass fraction changes.

322
00:14:53,940 --> 00:14:57,880
And every extra amount
that fraction gives you,

323
00:14:57,880 --> 00:15:01,200
we can move to payload, assuming
we're maxing out on payload.

324
00:15:01,200 --> 00:15:03,790
You could argue that some
payload is volume out.

325
00:15:03,790 --> 00:15:06,280
And so we want to
be able to do that.

326
00:15:06,280 --> 00:15:08,110
And that is where the
industry is moving.

327
00:15:08,110 --> 00:15:10,480
We're moving to
ever larger rockets.

328
00:15:10,480 --> 00:15:13,140
It's another place-- it's kind
of amazing how much the Apollo

329
00:15:13,140 --> 00:15:13,973
engineers had right.

