424
00:19:34,430 --> 00:19:36,500
which is with the
latest exploration--

425
00:19:36,500 --> 00:19:40,450
that's just again all come
about in the last decade or so--

426
00:19:40,450 --> 00:19:43,450
is now we have very
high confidence

427
00:19:43,450 --> 00:19:48,020
that water is on many parts
of the Moon and also on Mars.

428
00:19:48,020 --> 00:19:51,170
And this means you
can just crack H2O.

429
00:19:51,170 --> 00:19:55,060
And we can get both the
fuel and the oxidizer

430
00:19:55,060 --> 00:19:58,810
from hydrogen. And being able
to get that, if you just go back

431
00:19:58,810 --> 00:20:02,410
to the rocket equation, the
mass fraction would tell you--

432
00:20:02,410 --> 00:20:04,460
for all the things that
make this Earth great,

433
00:20:04,460 --> 00:20:05,840
the atmosphere is pretty good.

434
00:20:05,840 --> 00:20:06,670
I like it.

435
00:20:06,670 --> 00:20:08,840
Gravity, 1 G-- kind
of like 1 G, too.

436
00:20:08,840 --> 00:20:11,480
But it's pesky for rockets.

437
00:20:11,480 --> 00:20:15,980
So every time we have to
bring fuel up or oxidizer up,

438
00:20:15,980 --> 00:20:19,250
it's just mass, that if we
could build it in space,

439
00:20:19,250 --> 00:20:20,900
it's so much better.

440
00:20:20,900 --> 00:20:23,620
And so knowing that
we now have water

441
00:20:23,620 --> 00:20:27,230
on Earth-- on the Moon and
Mars and likely elsewhere,

442
00:20:27,230 --> 00:20:30,950
gives us high confidence that
hydrogen was the right choice.

443
00:20:30,950 --> 00:20:33,370
But again, I go back
to the Apollo era.

444
00:20:33,370 --> 00:20:35,270
And they had it right again.

445
00:20:35,270 --> 00:20:38,840
It's amazing how a bunch
of folks using slide rules

446
00:20:38,840 --> 00:20:40,940
had so many design decisions.

447
00:20:40,940 --> 00:20:42,630
But this is another
example of it,

448
00:20:42,630 --> 00:20:46,370
which is that you
really do like to have

449
00:20:46,370 --> 00:20:49,020
a carbon-based first stage
engine-- in our case,

450
00:20:49,020 --> 00:20:51,290
we're using liquid natural gas.

451
00:20:51,290 --> 00:20:58,924
But back in the Apollo days,
it was a different propellant--

452
00:20:58,924 --> 00:21:01,620
because you have such
good density from it.

453
00:21:01,620 --> 00:21:03,630
So you can pack a lot
more in your tanks.

454
00:21:03,630 --> 00:21:06,830
And while you're fighting that
atmospheric and gravitational

455
00:21:06,830 --> 00:21:09,290
drag, you can go ahead
and get through that.

456
00:21:09,290 --> 00:21:12,050
However, when you start
getting to upper stages

457
00:21:12,050 --> 00:21:15,170
and you're not
fighting those forces,

458
00:21:15,170 --> 00:21:17,210
you want to try to
get something that's

459
00:21:17,210 --> 00:21:18,840
much, much more efficient.

460
00:21:18,840 --> 00:21:21,300
And when you think
about ISP in an engine,

461
00:21:21,300 --> 00:21:24,090
the actual specific
impulse of the engine,

462
00:21:24,090 --> 00:21:26,150
there's really
almost nothing that

463
00:21:26,150 --> 00:21:31,050
beats the ability to put
hydrogen and oxygen together.

464
00:21:31,050 --> 00:21:32,400
And it just makes sense.

465
00:21:32,400 --> 00:21:36,860
And so we have chosen
that for those reasons.

466
00:21:36,860 --> 00:21:39,730
Now, there's obviously
downsides to this.

467
00:21:39,730 --> 00:21:42,700
I can make a lot of
arguments about why

468
00:21:42,700 --> 00:21:44,470
you wouldn't want
to do this, not

469
00:21:44,470 --> 00:21:47,150
the least of which is they're
entirely different engines,

470
00:21:47,150 --> 00:21:49,600
with entirely different cycles.

471
00:21:49,600 --> 00:21:52,180
So the logical choice, if
you're running a business,

472
00:21:52,180 --> 00:21:56,810
is to just say, OK, I'm going
to take my atmospheric engine

473
00:21:56,810 --> 00:22:00,050
and I am just going to
optimize a vacuum version of it

474
00:22:00,050 --> 00:22:01,400
and I'm going to call it a day.

475
00:22:01,400 --> 00:22:04,940
It's less test stands,
less infrastructure,

476
00:22:04,940 --> 00:22:07,870
less ability to have
things go wrong.

477
00:22:07,870 --> 00:22:12,040
But the right answer
architecturally,

478
00:22:12,040 --> 00:22:15,160
to create a hydrogen
economy, is to have

479
00:22:15,160 --> 00:22:16,790
optimized hydrogen engines.

480
00:22:16,790 --> 00:22:20,060
And we do it not only
in what you see here,

481
00:22:20,060 --> 00:22:21,800
which is-- this is the BE-3U.

482
00:22:21,800 --> 00:22:24,290
That was the upper stage
engines you saw on the video.

483
00:22:24,290 --> 00:22:27,110
And there's two of those
