00:23:24,320 --> 00:23:26,560
you can see the numbers
here-- as a percentage

504
00:23:26,560 --> 00:23:29,630
of where you are starts
to add up pretty quickly.

505
00:23:29,630 --> 00:23:32,670
And so you want to figure
out how are there ways

506
00:23:32,670 --> 00:23:34,780
that you can mitigate this?

507
00:23:34,780 --> 00:23:38,650
Again, insulation helps,
but in itself is not enough.

508
00:23:38,650 --> 00:23:40,860
And so, again,
thinking about what

509
00:23:40,860 --> 00:23:43,150
do you have to build to
do this hydrogen economy,

510
00:23:43,150 --> 00:23:45,820
it comes back to what
do you have to invent.

511
00:23:45,820 --> 00:23:49,090
And so in this case, you
want to invent a cryocooler.

512
00:23:49,090 --> 00:23:52,420
And so zero boiloff
cryocoolers-- by the way,

513
00:23:52,420 --> 00:23:54,730
cryocoolers are not
anything that's brand new.

514
00:23:54,730 --> 00:23:58,090
If you ever see somebody
with heat vision goggles--

515
00:23:58,090 --> 00:23:59,550
they have a version
of these kinds

516
00:23:59,550 --> 00:24:02,340
of things in miniature Stirling
engines and things like that,

517
00:24:02,340 --> 00:24:03,220
inside of them.

518
00:24:03,220 --> 00:24:07,600
But when you want
to do this in space,

519
00:24:07,600 --> 00:24:09,820
it's just never really
been done before.

520
00:24:09,820 --> 00:24:13,480
And you're talking about
liquid hydrogen, liquid oxygen.

521
00:24:13,480 --> 00:24:16,350
And you need to store them at
very, very low temperatures

522
00:24:16,350 --> 00:24:19,090
and in a vacuum.

523
00:24:19,090 --> 00:24:21,430
This is one of those
things where I say,

524
00:24:21,430 --> 00:24:24,900
when I got to Blue 18
months ago, I was actually--

525
00:24:24,900 --> 00:24:26,830
I was worried about
this invention.

526
00:24:26,830 --> 00:24:28,150
It had never been demonstrated.

527
00:24:28,150 --> 00:24:31,970
But we hit our NASA
milestone about two months

528
00:24:31,970 --> 00:24:34,098
ago or so, on Earth.

529
00:24:34,098 --> 00:24:35,640
So we still haven't
done it in space.

530
00:24:35,640 --> 00:24:37,470
But it was in vacuum on Earth.

531
00:24:37,470 --> 00:24:40,710
We demonstrated that we
were able to, in vacuum,

532
00:24:40,710 --> 00:24:42,535
keep at 20k and 90k.

533
00:24:42,535 --> 00:24:43,910
Those are the
stable temperatures

534
00:24:43,910 --> 00:24:45,860
that we need to
keep liquid hydrogen

535
00:24:45,860 --> 00:24:48,360
and oxygen from boiling off.

536
00:24:48,360 --> 00:24:50,520
And so it's a huge
milestone change.

537
00:24:50,520 --> 00:24:53,780
Again, hard problem--
but if we can knock down

538
00:24:53,780 --> 00:24:55,910
these hard problems,
we can actually

539
00:24:55,910 --> 00:25:00,980
get the incredible foundation
of this hydrogen ecosystem

540
00:25:00,980 --> 00:25:02,570
in space.

541
00:25:02,570 --> 00:25:06,570
So we talked about reducing the
cost of space at least to orbit.

542
00:25:06,570 --> 00:25:09,290
We've talked about building
a hydrogen economy.

543
00:25:09,290 --> 00:25:12,530
Third, I would
postulate that the Moon

544
00:25:12,530 --> 00:25:14,570
is our strategic gateway.

545
00:25:14,570 --> 00:25:17,750
And this may not be the
common wisdom across all space

546
00:25:17,750 --> 00:25:19,290
companies, but it is ours.

547
00:25:19,290 --> 00:25:25,020
And I don't know where you all
fall down on the Fermi paradox.

548
00:25:25,020 --> 00:25:28,250
But if you're in
the simulation camp,

549
00:25:28,250 --> 00:25:30,930
the Moon would be a cheat code.

550
00:25:30,930 --> 00:25:35,330
I mean, who would possibly
put this body three days away

551
00:25:35,330 --> 00:25:41,000
from Earth, no atmosphere, with
asteroids and meteorites hitting

552
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:43,730
it for millions of
years, guaranteed

553
00:25:43,730 --> 00:25:49,527
to have every element
known to personkind on it.

554
00:25:49,527 --> 00:25:51,110
You would never have
guessed something

555
00:25:51,110 --> 00:25:52,735
like this could
possibly have happened.

556
00:25:52,735 --> 00:25:53,777
But, indeed, it is there.

557
00:25:53,777 --> 00:25:55,443
And I don't think
we're in a simulation.

558
00:25:55,443 --> 00:25:56,700
So we're going to use it.

559
00:25:56,700 --> 00:25:58,070
[LAUGHTER]

560
00:25:58,070 --> 00:26:04,710
And it's our mine, our resource
depot, three days away.

561
00:26:04,710 --> 00:26:08,190
And it's incredibly
rich in resources.

562
00:26:08,190 --> 00:26:10,440
And it's something
that we really want.

563
00:26:10,440 --> 00:26:11,160
We want to do.

564
00:26:11,160 --> 00:26:14,150
So a lot of what we're
doing is thinking

565
00:26:14,150 --> 00:26:16,830
about going back to the Moon.

566
00:26:16,830 --> 00:26:20,070
But it's not just about
going back to the Moon.

567
00:26:20,070 --> 00:26:23,160
In fact, our lunar team
is not called Lunar.

568
00:26:23,160 --> 00:26:24,960
It's called Lunar Permanence.

569
00:26:24,960 --> 00:26:26,160
We've been to the Moon.

570
00:26:26,160 --> 00:26:29,300
We've been there and back
a few times, a dozen times.

571
00:26:29,300 --> 00:26:31,660
But we didn't stick.

572
00:26:31,660 --> 00:26:33,400
And that was an
amazing accomplishment,

573
00:26:33,400 --> 00:26:34,900
by the way-- probably
fast-forwarded

574
00:26:34,900 --> 00:26:37,400
the Moon 20 years, the
Apollo program, if not more.

575
00:26:37,400 --> 00:26:40,130
But now you want to
go there to stay.

576
00:26:40,130 --> 00:26:43,690
And you want to go
there and be able to use

577
00:26:43,690 --> 00:26:47,600
the resources that are up there
in clever and innovative ways.

578
00:26:47,600 --> 00:26:49,010
So how are we doing that?

579
00:26:49,010 --> 00:26:51,020
Well, we're going to
do it in two steps.

580
00:26:51,020 --> 00:26:53,800
This is the original
Apollo lunar

581
00:26:53,800 --> 00:26:55,490
module, the LEM on top of it.

582
00:26:55,490 --> 00:26:58,850
Our first vehicle, that you see
here, is our Mark 1 vehicle.

583
00:26:58,850 --> 00:27:01,670
It is in final
assembly right now.

584
00:27:01,670 --> 00:27:05,450
It's just about to go off to
vacuum test in a little bit.

585
00:27:05,450 --> 00:27:07,520
And it is a cargo lander.

586
00:27:07,520 --> 00:27:12,940
And we'll go to the Moon, first
quarter of next year probably,

587
00:27:12,940 --> 00:27:14,150
in that range.

588
00:27:14,150 --> 00:27:17,710
And it will be the
biggest vehicle

589
00:27:17,710 --> 00:27:20,467
to have ever landed on the Moon.

590
00:27:20,467 --> 00:27:21,800
We're not going to make it easy.

591
00:27:21,800 --> 00:27:23,120
We're going to do a
triple Lindy here.

592
00:27:23,120 --> 00:27:25,537
We're going to land it on near
the south pole of the Moon.

593
00:27:25,537 --> 00:27:28,450
So it's a big
effort for the team.

594
00:27:28,450 --> 00:27:30,520
But just to put
that in comparison,

595
00:27:30,520 --> 00:27:32,880
then contrast it to
what we call Mark 2--

596
00:27:32,880 --> 00:27:34,230
by the way, Mark 1--

597
00:27:34,230 --> 00:27:37,810
we just won a NASA contract
to take Viper to the Moon.

598
00:27:37,810 --> 00:27:39,690
So it'll be serial
number 2 of Mark 1

599
00:27:39,690 --> 00:27:41,260
will take Viper to the Moon.

600
00:27:41,260 --> 00:27:45,910
And then next to it is the
human-rated Mark 2 vehicle.

601
00:27:45,910 --> 00:27:47,800
We're also doing a
cargo version of that.

602
00:27:47,800 --> 00:27:49,720
But to give you a sense
of the scale of that,

603
00:27:49,720 --> 00:27:51,490
it's 15 meters tall--

604
00:27:51,490 --> 00:27:54,340
30 metric tons to
the lunar surface.

605
00:27:54,340 --> 00:27:57,750
So this is the
semi-truck that is

606
00:27:57,750 --> 00:28:00,480
going to be able to
pull lots of cargo

607
00:28:00,480 --> 00:28:03,690
down to the Moon to allow
us to get that permanence

608
00:28:03,690 --> 00:28:06,600
and begin to plant the
seeds for a permanent base

609
00:28:06,600 --> 00:28:09,600
there, that we can then-- again,
manufacturing, mine the Moon,

610
00:28:09,600 --> 00:28:12,270
and begin to build the
infrastructure there to hop

611
00:28:12,270 --> 00:28:13,540
off to the rest.

612
00:28:13,540 --> 00:28:17,190
And so you can see an incredible
amount of difference in mass

613
00:28:17,190 --> 00:28:20,740
from where the Apollo
missions were up until--

614
00:28:20,740 --> 00:28:21,790
that might be a typo.

615
00:28:21,790 --> 00:28:24,970
I think it's 30 metric
tons, but I could be wrong.

616
00:28:24,970 --> 00:28:29,350
So what do we have to
do to make the Moon more

617
00:28:29,350 --> 00:28:31,120
interesting in terms
of infrastructure--

618
00:28:31,120 --> 00:28:32,950
back to the same things.

619
00:28:32,950 --> 00:28:35,320
Actually, this is going to
seem very duplicative to some

620
00:28:35,320 --> 00:28:36,820
of the students
that presented to me

621
00:28:36,820 --> 00:28:40,910
earlier on your
own class project,

622
00:28:40,910 --> 00:28:44,650
or I guess NASA project,
for being able to navigate

623
00:28:44,650 --> 00:28:46,340
autonomously on the Moon.

624
00:28:46,340 --> 00:28:48,100
We're going to have
to build vehicles

625
00:28:48,100 --> 00:28:49,580
that can traverse the Moon.

626
00:28:49,580 --> 00:28:51,460
Some are going to
do mining, some

627
00:28:51,460 --> 00:28:53,150
are going to be
to do exploration,

628
00:28:53,150 --> 00:28:54,500
some are going to be transport.

629
00:28:54,500 --> 00:28:56,440
And the first stages
of this are how

630
00:28:56,440 --> 00:28:59,450
do we build a rover that
can be able to do this?

631
00:28:59,450 --> 00:29:01,990
And I know you guys--
the Maple team, which

632
00:29:01,990 --> 00:29:03,850
I saw present earlier
today, it was just

633
00:29:03,850 --> 00:29:06,320
great to see the
progress you made.

634
00:29:06,320 --> 00:29:08,980
Second place is a huge
achievement in this.

635
00:29:08,980 --> 00:29:10,930
And I was sitting
there biting my tongue

636
00:29:10,930 --> 00:29:13,270
because I know how hard the
problem is, because I meet

637
00:29:13,270 --> 00:29:14,890
with this team every
two weeks and I

638
00:29:14,890 --> 00:29:16,430
get a sense of what's going on.

639
00:29:16,430 --> 00:29:25,350
So our effort here is to start
taking payloads up to the Moon.

640
00:29:25,350 --> 00:29:28,190
Our first one will be on
Firefly's next lander.

641
00:29:28,190 --> 00:29:30,900
Our honeybee team
is doing the rover.

642
00:29:30,900 --> 00:29:33,050
And it will be a
traditional rover

643
00:29:33,050 --> 00:29:34,590
in every sense of the word.

644
00:29:34,590 --> 00:29:35,400
It's lower cost.

645
00:29:35,400 --> 00:29:40,080
But it will be teleoperated
and be able to be teleoperated.

646
00:29:40,080 --> 00:29:42,300
But we're, in
parallel with that,

647
00:29:42,300 --> 00:29:44,870
going to put a complete
autonomous package on it,

648
00:29:44,870 --> 00:29:47,960
so that we, in parallel, can
run experiments about what does

649
00:29:47,960 --> 00:29:49,620
autonomy look like on the Moon?

650
00:29:49,620 --> 00:29:51,920
So that vehicles after
that and after that

651
00:29:51,920 --> 00:29:55,380
will get steadily more
advanced as we move through.

652
00:29:55,380 --> 00:29:58,460
And I think, again, it was
one of those things that

653
00:29:58,460 --> 00:30:03,540
was shown in very, very
good detail earlier today.

654
00:30:03,540 --> 00:30:06,650
But having worked on
autonomous vehicles

655
00:30:06,650 --> 00:30:10,190
for a lot of the last
10 years of my life--

656
00:30:10,190 --> 00:30:13,700
Zoox was in my team at Amazon--

657
00:30:13,700 --> 00:30:17,780
much of the problem of
getting autonomy working

658
00:30:17,780 --> 00:30:19,662
is a data problem.

659
00:30:19,662 --> 00:30:22,190
That's why when you go
around San Francisco,

660
00:30:22,190 --> 00:30:24,500
you see lots of Waymo
cars with a driver in it,

661
00:30:24,500 --> 00:30:26,210
with sensors on it or Zoox cars.

662
00:30:26,210 --> 00:30:28,420
They are training
up the road systems

663
00:30:28,420 --> 00:30:30,190
and getting data
and understanding

664
00:30:30,190 --> 00:30:32,900
what are the anomalous things
that happen in traffic.

665
00:30:32,900 --> 00:30:36,670
Last time I checked, we
don't have those on the Moon.

666
00:30:36,670 --> 00:30:39,880
And, in fact, you could say,
oh, but wasn't Apollo up there

667
00:30:39,880 --> 00:30:40,580
with a rover?

668
00:30:40,580 --> 00:30:43,960
Yes-- but the
cameras, not so good.

669
00:30:43,960 --> 00:30:45,050
They were running.

670
00:30:45,050 --> 00:30:47,410
I think there's seven
hours of true video.

671
00:30:47,410 --> 00:30:48,910
But when you back
it off, it ends up

672
00:30:48,910 --> 00:30:51,070
being about an hour
because it was running

673
00:30:51,070 --> 00:30:52,810
at 12 frames per second.

674
00:30:52,810 --> 00:30:55,040
It only took a snapshot
every so often.

675
00:30:55,040 --> 00:30:56,810
And so we do have that data.

676
00:30:56,810 --> 00:31:00,250
But it is not
representative of what

677
00:31:00,250 --> 00:31:02,900
you're going to see, especially
at different parts of the Moon.

678
00:31:02,900 --> 00:31:05,440
As you get to the poles,
obviously, the lighting

679
00:31:05,440 --> 00:31:07,360
conditions change dramatically.

680
00:31:07,360 --> 00:31:10,728
And you can be in night
for a long period of time.

681
00:31:10,728 --> 00:31:12,770
You can be in sunlight
for a long period of time.

682
00:31:12,770 --> 00:31:16,700
And so the navigation challenge
becomes incredibly complicated.

683
00:31:16,700 --> 00:31:19,220
And so what we're able to
do through simulation--

684
00:31:19,220 --> 00:31:22,740
this is actually a game engine
running our lunar terrain

685
00:31:22,740 --> 00:31:24,340
scenarios internally.

686
00:31:24,340 --> 00:31:28,360
And we can then do a digital
twin of what a rover looks like.

687
00:31:28,360 --> 00:31:30,330
And we can try different
sensor packages

688
00:31:30,330 --> 00:31:33,550
and say, huh, I wonder if it'd
be better with stereo optics

689
00:31:33,550 --> 00:31:34,780
or it'd be better with LiDAR?

690
00:31:34,780 --> 00:31:38,350
Would it be better if we
had a really good IMU?

691
00:31:38,350 --> 00:31:41,460
Or should we figure out
a way that the lander has

692
00:31:41,460 --> 00:31:43,170
really, really
interesting beacons

693
00:31:43,170 --> 00:31:45,600
and use trigonometry to
figure the problem out.

694
00:31:45,600 --> 00:31:47,740
There's lots of different
ways you can solve this.

695
00:31:47,740 --> 00:31:50,920
But it turns out to be a
pretty tractable problem.

696
00:31:50,920 --> 00:31:52,770
And we are very
excited about where

697
00:31:52,770 --> 00:31:54,010
we're going to get to here.

698
00:31:54,010 --> 00:31:55,780
The other thing about the Moon--

699
00:31:55,780 --> 00:31:58,070
I talked about how
resource-rich it is--

700
00:31:58,070 --> 00:32:01,540
is that you don't
have to go very far.

701
00:32:01,540 --> 00:32:03,360
I was implying
that you could dig

702
00:32:03,360 --> 00:32:05,370
and you'd find platinum
here and gold there

703
00:32:05,370 --> 00:32:06,930
and unobtainium there.

704
00:32:06,930 --> 00:32:07,840
That's true.

705
00:32:07,840 --> 00:32:09,490
I'm very big an
optimist on that.

706
00:32:09,490 --> 00:32:14,530
But the regolith itself is
incredibly rich in resources.

707
00:32:14,530 --> 00:32:18,040
So we have a whole different
team called Blue Alchemist.

708
00:32:18,040 --> 00:32:20,460
Again, infrastructure--
figuring out

709
00:32:20,460 --> 00:32:25,300
how to build reactors that
can be powered on the Moon,

710
00:32:25,300 --> 00:32:29,500
but that you can just put in one
side of this robotic reactor,

711
00:32:29,500 --> 00:32:33,270
throw the regolith in it, and
literally out the other end

712
00:32:33,270 --> 00:32:35,830
is going to come a
silicon solar panel.

713
00:32:35,830 --> 00:32:39,250
And this has been proven in our
labs already in the piece parts.

714
00:32:39,250 --> 00:32:41,040
And we're now in the
formulation stage

715
00:32:41,040 --> 00:32:43,090
of putting that all together.

716
00:32:43,090 --> 00:32:49,170
And in our labs, in California,
we're getting purities

717
00:32:49,170 --> 00:32:51,970
of silicon at more than,
I guess, three or four--

718
00:32:51,970 --> 00:32:55,210
five 9s at this point, 99.999%.

719
00:32:55,210 --> 00:32:58,980
So this is incredibly optimistic
to be able to now create

720
00:32:58,980 --> 00:33:00,100
power on the Moon.

721
00:33:00,100 --> 00:33:03,270
And once we crack
silica and that,

722
00:33:03,270 --> 00:33:06,150
the refining process
actually works across a lot

723
00:33:06,150 --> 00:33:07,390
of different types of things.

724
00:33:07,390 --> 00:33:10,650
So the more we find out
about regolith and what's

725
00:33:10,650 --> 00:33:15,390
there and one layer below,
the more this on premise, on

726
00:33:15,390 --> 00:33:20,180
lunar ability to be able
to get rich resources

727
00:33:20,180 --> 00:33:23,450
is really going to
be game changing

728
00:33:23,450 --> 00:33:24,990
in a sense of infrastructure.

729
00:33:24,990 --> 00:33:26,480
Again, it's just
less payload you

730
00:33:26,480 --> 00:33:28,230
have to bring from other Earth.

731
00:33:28,230 --> 00:33:30,475
The final thing I want
to talk about in terms

732
00:33:30,475 --> 00:33:32,850
of infrastructure-- we've
talked about lowering the cost,

733
00:33:32,850 --> 00:33:36,770
hydrogen economy, use this cheat
code of the moon as a stepping

734
00:33:36,770 --> 00:33:37,490
stone--

735
00:33:37,490 --> 00:33:40,560
is building comms
infrastructure.

736
00:33:40,560 --> 00:33:43,340
If there's anything
we've learned on Earth,

737
00:33:43,340 --> 00:33:47,150
is that comms communications
infrastructure

738
00:33:47,150 --> 00:33:48,990
is incredibly important.

739
00:33:48,990 --> 00:33:56,823
The amount of just exponential
growth in both free speech

740
00:33:56,823 --> 00:33:58,740
and the ability to
understand what's going on,

741
00:33:58,740 --> 00:34:01,790
because we have open comms
systems and effectively

742
00:34:01,790 --> 00:34:04,190
unlimited bandwidth in
lots of parts of the Earth,

743
00:34:04,190 --> 00:34:07,010
has changed how we think
about our social life.

744
00:34:07,010 --> 00:34:09,510
It certainly thinks about how
we change about our work life.

745
00:34:09,510 --> 00:34:10,949
It changes productivity.

746
00:34:10,949 --> 00:34:13,219
There's no reason to believe
that that's not going

747
00:34:13,219 --> 00:34:14,760
to be true in space as well.

748
00:34:14,760 --> 00:34:17,065
